Title: Non-Gaussian Density Perturbations in Inflationary Cosmologies  
Author: T. J. Allen, B. Grinstein and Mark B. Wise 
Note: Work supported in part by the U.S. Department of Energy under Contracts DEAC-03-81-ER40050 and DE-FG03-84-ER40172. Sloan Fellow.  
Address: Pasadena, CA 91125  
Affiliation: California Institute of Technology,  
Abstract: CALT-68-1427 DOE RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT REPORT Abstract The primordial mass density fluctuations may have arisen from quantum fluctuations in a (massless) scalar field that occurred during an inflationary era. We show that it is possible for primordial mass density fluctuations, which arose in this way, to be highly non-Gaussian. We also show that the "bad" infrared properties of the propagator for a massless scalar field in de Sitter space can translate itself into a power spectrum, for the the two-point spatial correlation of objects that do not trace the mass, which behaves like k 3 , at small wave numbers k. 
